# stencil_bench — the hot-loop cost of the corrected finite-volume scheme
#
# Answers `grid-comparison-report.md` §10.6: the corrected scheme is a 5x5 solve
# per cell per step; nobody had benchmarked it, and the precomputed-stencil rescue
# was an INFERENCE. Both are measured here, on real cube-sphere geometry, on the
# dense Cartesian tile layout `erosion.rs` actually uses.

## 0. A REFUTED HYPOTHESIS (recorded as a result)

`probes::lsq_gradients_quadratic` fits `[x, y, x²/2, xy, y²/2]` with x, y in **metres**,
so at L6 (~156 km cells) the quadratic columns are ~1e5x the linear ones. The normal
equations are correspondingly ill-conditioned — cond(AᵀA) is the SQUARE of cond(A):

| level | cell size | cond(AᵀA), as written | cond(AᵀA), nondimensionalised |
|---|---|---|---|
| L6 |   156352 m | 1.22e10 | 8.00e0 |
| L9 |    19546 m | 1.91e8 | 8.00e0 |
| L12 |     2443 m | 2.98e6 | 8.00e0 |
| L15 |      305 m | 4.66e4 | 8.00e0 |
| L19 |       19 m | 1.82e2 | 8.00e0 |

I PREDICTED this meant part of the report's 3.65e-4 was conditioning noise, and that
the scheme would look better once conditioned. §A tests it on the report's own harness.
**It is refuted**: the fix changes the answer by 1.7e-14. The error lands in the
ill-determined QUADRATIC directions; the two linear components actually read out are
recovered accurately anyway. The report's number is truncation error, as claimed. [M]

What survives, and is operationally load-bearing: **cond 1.2e10 ≫ f32's ~1e7 range, so
the 5x5 solve can never be done in f32.** It bears on HOW the precomputed weights must
be built (in f64, once), not on what the scheme's accuracy is. [M]

## A. VERIFICATION — the dense kernels vs. the report's own reference implementation

The oracle is `grid_lab`'s `probes::laplacian(Scheme::FvLsq)` on `grids::cube_sphere`
(equiangular, n=64 ⇒ L6, 24 576 cells — the report's own size). A dense tile is cut
from the interior of face 0 and every kernel is compared CELL FOR CELL.

- my lifted edge_flux vs probes::laplacian(FvLsq) : rel L2 = 1.38e-14

  §0's prediction, tested on the report's own harness (whole-sphere, 24 576 cells):
  - `probes::harmonic_error(FvLsq)`, verbatim     : 3.645e-4   ← the report's table says 3.65e-4
  - FvLsq AS WRITTEN (normal equations in metres) : rel L2 vs exact = 3.770e-4
  - FvLsq NONDIMENSIONALISED (cond 1e10 -> 8.0)   : rel L2 vs exact = 3.770e-4
  - the two answers differ from each other by       rel L2 = 1.732e-14
  ⇒ §0's hypothesis is REFUTED. The conditioning is real and harmless; the report's
    accuracy number is truncation error, not round-off. [M]

- cell centres    : max |Δ| = 0.000e0  (unit vectors)
- cell areas      : max rel Δ = 0.000e0
- Moore-set mismatches : 0
- edge transmissibility: max rel Δ = 0.000e0
- edge offset w_i      : max |Δ| = 0.000e0 m
- edge offset w_j      : max |Δ| = 0.000e0 m
- K3 (5x5 solve/cell/step, dense) vs the mesh oracle : rel L2 = 3.964e-15   ← must be round-off
- GRADIENT: dense vs mesh, max |Δ| = 4.314e-21  (|∇u| ~ 2.354e-7)  ⇒ rel 1.833e-14
    ring 0 from interior edge ( 124 cells): max rel Δ = 4.160e-12
    ring 1 from interior edge ( 116 cells): max rel Δ = 4.997e-12
    ring 2 from interior edge ( 108 cells): max rel Δ = 1.712e-12
    ring 3 from interior edge ( 100 cells): max rel Δ = 5.179e-13
    ring 4 from interior edge (  92 cells): max rel Δ = 1.387e-12
    ring 5 from interior edge ( 484 cells): max rel Δ = 3.752e-12
- K5 (precomputed FUSED 21-pt, f64) vs K3  : L2 = 2.738e-13   ← must be round-off

  ⇒ The precomputed 21-point stencil is an EXACT algebraic refactor of the corrected
    scheme, not an approximation. Same operator, same numbers, to round-off. [M]

## B. ACCURACY — what the correction buys, and what the cheap forms give back

Relative L2 error of the discrete Laplace-Beltrami operator against the EXACT
eigenvalue of an l=2 harmonic, measured on a 64x64 tile of real cube-sphere geometry.

| level | cell | naive 5-pt | FV 2-point | CORRECTED (exact) | fused f32 | frozen-const f32 |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| L6 | 143921 m | 1.63e-1 | 2.90e-1 | **1.64e-4** | 1.79e-4 | 1.57e-1 |
| L9 | 19515 m | 4.40e-3 | 2.34e-2 | **3.51e-6** | 3.89e-3 | 6.29e-3 |
| L12 | 2443 m | 7.02e-5 | 2.80e-3 | **5.52e-8** | 2.63e-1 | 3.15e-1 |

⚠ The harmonic is SMOOTH: at fine levels its second difference falls below f32
  epsilon and the f32 columns measure catastrophic cancellation in the TEST FIELD,
  not error in the scheme. The honest f32 question is asked on rough terrain:

L19, 64x64 tile, rough terrain (6 octaves, ~1.5 km relief over 1.2 km, ~19 m cells).
Three DIFFERENT questions, separated — the first run conflated them:

| what is being isolated | weights | field | rel L2 vs exact-f64 |
|---|---|---|---|
| **f32 FIELD** rounding (the deployed precision) | f32 | f32 | 3.064e-3 |
| **f32 WEIGHT** rounding alone | f32 | f64 | 3.925e-9 |
| **the FROZEN approximation** alone | const, f64 | f64 | 5.070e-9 |
| frozen + f32 (what you would ship) | const, f32 | f32 | 3.064e-3 |

⇒ The f32 FIELD dominates: storing the weights in f32 is ~free (3.9e-9), and the
  frozen-constant approximation is ALSO ~free at L19 (5.1e-9) — a 64-cell tile spans
  1.2e-4 of a face, over which the metric is essentially constant. Both are swamped
  by the f32 height field vivarium already uses. [M]

## C. COST — cell-updates/s at L19, TILE_NX = 64 (what the builder actually sweeps)

| kernel | cell-updates/s (median of 9) | run-to-run | vs baseline | coeff B/cell |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| K0 naive 5-pt (BASELINE = today) | **3.21 G** | ±0.6% | 1.000x | 0 |
|   [noise-floor control: K0 again] | **3.26 G** | ±0.9% | 1.017x | 0 |
| K1 FV two-point, true metric | **1.69 G** | ±0.4% | 0.525x | 20 |
| K3 CORRECTED, 5x5 solve/cell/step | **4.1 M** | ±0.5% | 0.001x | 0 (solved live) |
| K2 CORRECTED + metric rebuilt/step | **1.2 M** | ±1.0% | 0.000x | 0 (solved live) |
| K4 PRECOMPUTED fused 21-pt (SoA) | **265.5 M** | ±0.9% | 0.083x | 84 (21 f32) |
|   [K4 with AoS weights — layout cost] | **89.6 M** | ±5.0% | 0.028x | 84 (21 f32) |
| K5 PRECOMPUTED fused 21-pt, f64 | **166.4 M** | ±0.4% | 0.052x | 168 (21 f64) |
| K6 PRECOMPUTED two-pass (keeps fluxes) | **73.9 M** | ±3.2% | 0.023x | 148 |
| K7 FROZEN const-coeff 21-pt (APPROX) | **384.5 M** | ±1.1% | 0.120x | 0 (in registers) |

Precompute, once per tile (amortised over the tile's steps):
- tile geometry (centres, areas, 4 edges/cell) : 2.40 ms  (64x64)
- fused 21-pt weights (the 5x5 inverse/cell)   : 4.40 ms
- break-even vs re-solving every step          : 6.92 steps
  (i.e. the precompute pays for itself almost immediately; erosion runs 100s-1000s of steps/tile)

## D. THE CACHE CLIFF — where each scheme falls out of L2 (this machine: 16 MB)

The coefficient stream is 84 B/cell against the field's 4 B/cell — 21x. So the
corrected scheme should meet the cliff when 84·N² ≈ 16 MB, i.e. N ≈ 437. Predicted
BEFORE measuring; the sweep is deliberately dense across that point.

| patch | cells | field MB | coeff MB | K0 naive | K4 fused f32 | K7 frozen |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| 64² | 4096 | 0.02 | 0.3 | 3.49 G (±1.1%) | **278.7 M** (±4.9%) | 361.7 M (±3.4%) |
| 128² | 16384 | 0.07 | 1.4 | 4.37 G (±2.5%) | **293.7 M** (±4.7%) | 465.9 M (±0.1%) |
| 256² | 65536 | 0.27 | 5.5 | 4.37 G (±0.7%) | **284.8 M** (±1.0%) | 558.4 M (±0.2%) |
| 384² | 147456 | 0.60 | 12.4 | 4.93 G (±2.8%) | **289.3 M** (±6.6%) | 620.1 M (±0.5%) |
| 512² | 262144 | 1.07 | 22.0 | 4.79 G (±1.8%) | **224.4 M** (±15.2%) | 627.6 M (±0.6%) |
| 768² | 589824 | 2.38 | 49.5 | 4.98 G (±2.9%) | **195.3 M** (±2.2%) | 634.3 M (±0.9%) |
| 1024² | 1048576 | 4.23 | 88.1 | 3.13 G (±1.9%) | **158.1 M** (±5.1%) | 467.9 M (±0.1%) |
| 2048² | 4194304 | 16.84 | 352.3 | 3.32 G (±4.7%) | **205.7 M** (±1.0%) | 483.0 M (±0.7%) |

## E. CONSERVATION, AND WHERE THE FROZEN STENCIL BREAKS

Operator applied ONCE to a compactly-supported bump (all boundary fluxes = 0):
`Σ Aᵢ·Δuᵢ` must be EXACTLY zero for a conservative scheme.

| kernel | Σ Aᵢ·Δuᵢ / Σ Aᵢ·|Δuᵢ| | exactly conservative? |
|---|---|---|
| K4/K5 PRECOMPUTED fused (per-cell) | +1.99e-14 | **YES** (round-off) |
| K7 FROZEN const-coeff | -2.85e-10 | **NO** — a real leak |

The frozen stencil's other exposure — the metric is worst at a face CORNER, not centre:

| tile position on face (L19) | frozen-vs-exact rel L2 (f64) |
|---|---|
| face centre | 5.07e-9 |
| mid-face | 3.98e-5 |
| near face edge | 8.89e-5 |
| face CORNER | 6.93e-5 |

## F. WHAT THIS COSTS *EROSION* — the stencil is one pass inside a much bigger epoch

Real `Fluvial::erode`, L19, 64x64 tile, 40 epochs (the CLI's default):

| | µs per epoch per tile | share of the epoch |
|---|---|---|
| **the whole epoch** (Priority-Flood + sort + routing + incise + deposit + talus + creep) | 540.0 | 100% |
| `creep` — the ONE 5-point Laplacian pass in it (today) | 1.28 | 0.24% |
| the same pass, CORRECTED **as written** (K3, 5x5 solve/cell/step) | 999 | 185% |
| the same pass, CORRECTED + **precomputed** (K4) | 15.75 | 2.9% |

| what an erosion EPOCH costs | µs | vs today |
|---|---|---|
| today (naive creep) | 540 | 1.00x |
| corrected, AS WRITTEN | 1538 | **2.85x** |
| corrected, PRECOMPUTED | 555 | **1.027x** |

⚠ READ BOTH TABLES TOGETHER. "790x slower" is TRUE of the stencil and MISLEADING
  about erosion: it is a ratio on a term that is 0.24% of the epoch. Even the
  UNRESCUED scheme only makes an erosion epoch 2.8x slower. The precomputed
  form makes it 1.027x. Quoting the stencil ratio as the cost to vivarium would be
  the alarming number winning because it is louder. [M]

⇒ Replacing creep's stencil with the corrected one adds **14.5 µs/epoch**, i.e.
  **+2.7% on a full erosion epoch** — not +1130%. The 12.3x is a ratio on a term
  that is 0.24% of the work. [M]

⚠ AND THE HONEST LIMIT OF THAT: `creep` is the only pass the fused-Laplacian form
  can replace. The Prime Question's actual target is **MFD routing**, which needs
  materialised per-edge FLUXES and therefore the two-pass form (K6), and which sits
  inside the Priority-Flood/sort/accumulate block — the expensive part. **That
  substitution is NOT measured here and it is the residue of this spike.** Do not
  read '+2.7% on an epoch' as the cost of fixing MFD.

